Mar 28 2007	Great hotel for shopaholic tourists	My stay at the Jumeirah Carlton Tower was work-related so I didn't spend much time walking around the area except to go to and from the tube. The neighborhood is terrible for those of traveling for business in the financial field but GREAT for those who have high-end shopping tastes. Harrods &amp; Harvey Nichols are both within walking distance. Tons of other high-end luxury shops are also right outside your doorstep.The rooms are quite small but that is to be expected in any London hotel. I'm from New York City so I'm used to small hotel rooms. Room service was surprisingly yummy and the afternoon tea in the lobby area is a must for all visitors.There was a homeless man who set up a home right across the street from the entrance to hotel, which is along a cute little park. That was a bit discerning considering the number of stars this hotel has.	
Mar 28 2007 	Bless 'em	I adored this hotel. I had a awful trip into London, but was taken care of once I arrived at the hotel. Check in was quick, the lady showed me to my room, giving a tour of the hotel on the way, and ensuring I was show the features of the room and how to use the services. Room service was prompt, and fantastic value, although I couldn't eat it all! Taxis were always available when leaving the hotel, and the conciergewas helpful in terms of providing advice and directions.The service was personal, and thoughtful. The availablility of staff fluent in a huge variety of languages (including Lithuanian!!) was fantastic. 3 minor downfalls were slack service in the coffee lounge area (as in I had to leave a huge tip because no-one came to collect the money and I had a plane to catch), the minibar was not refilled on one occassion, and the goods posted back to me were not sent via express post as requested. Each of these I could have rectified, but didn't because the overall experience was fantastic, from making the reservation, to the follow-up once back home.	
Feb 20 2007 	Very Average for a Five Star Hotel	I just spent the weekend at this hotel with my husband. Firstly, I must point out there was scaffolding up and there were building works going on even on the Sunday. Unless you do not mind waking up to building site noises I would recommend you contact the hotel before booking here to find out if the works have completed. Other than that, we stayed in a deluxe room on the eighth floor. The room was spacious, unfortunately the décor of the room was a bit bland and needed updating. Parts of the wallpaper were peeling and the furniture looked tired, dusty and worn out. The room was decorated in shades of brown and cream, the room looked like a dreary old-fashioned version of the photos on their website. There is a plasma TV on a stand and a Bose CD player which is played at turndown. Parts of the room did not make sense, for example there were paintings on the wall behind the TV, it seemed as if no thought was put in when decorating the place, it all appeared very boringly standard. At turndown, the hotel did provide complimentary bottled water and cookies which was a nice touch. There is a strange heating system in that every time the level of heating is adjusted the radiator makes strange noises for about 5 minutes, we were informed by their engineer that this is the case in every room. The view from the bedroom was disappointingly of the back of other buildings, the hotel is however well located for Harrods, Harvey Nicks and Sloane Street shopping. Check in did take a little longer than expected, however the staff were polite and courteous. Overall, it is a very standard place to stay, there was nothing striking or impressive about it and I doubt I shall be returning.	
Jan 17 2007 	Very pampery indeed	We had a one-night stay here. With very few exceptions, everything about the stay was excellent. We arrived early (11.15am), check-in was quick and polite (hot towels to freshen up at reception), and because our room wasn't ready (we weren't actually expecting it to be...), we were offered complimentary tea and biscuits in the Chinoiserie lounge. We left our bags with reception and they were taken to our room while we were out.Our room was beautiful, comfortable, well equipped, fresh fruit and mineral water, good toiletries etc. The TV wasn't working, but an engineer came up immediately and sorted out the problem. The spa and pool were excellent and being used very little so we had the pool and jacuzzi to ourselves most of the time we were there. We also had very good massages on the 9th floor, and a very nice healthy lunch at the Spa restaurant/bar. Breakfast was outstanding - a very good traditional English and a well equipped buffet table. Everywhere was clean, everyone was extremely polite and helpful, we had no problems with the lifts (which were quick too) I guess anyone's perceptions of a 5 star hotel will be determined by what they're used to. We're certainly not used to staying in such hotels at all, and for us this place was a real treat. Perhaps if you always stay in 5 star hotels, you're able to compare them more critically with others. For us though, this was the most comfortable experience we've ever had in a hotel.	
Jan 9 2007 	Nothing to write home about	Stayed at the hotel only for one night while in London on business. Whereas the location cannot be doubted, being a stone's throw away from Knightsbridge (Harrods, Harvey Nics) and Sloane Sq., the overall experience was pretty average.I have not stayed at this hotel before the acquisition by Jumeirah so am not in a position to comment on the changes. However, I found the overall level of service to be pretty ordinary be it at the reception, conceirge or room service. Some of the common areas (especially the corridors on the room floors) also look and feel pretty dated. The room, while pretty functional and having a nice view over Cadogan place, was incredibly small and almost difficult to move around despite the very average double bed. Though one has to bear in mind that this is a typical problem of many central london hotels. The smallness of size extended to the bathroom but the water pressure in the shower was good which was a relief.Overall, I found it to be a pleasant enough experience and decent value for money (by London standards!) but there was nothing to make me the stay in any way special.	
